  "prompt": "Can someone build a product based on an idea he pitched to his ex company, if the company never cared to productize it?",
  "response": "The ability to build a product based on an idea you pitched to your former company depends on several factors, including the specifics of your situation, intellectual property laws, and any agreements you may have signed while employed.\n\nHere are some key considerations:\n\n1. **Employment Agreements**: Review any employment contracts, non-disclosure agreements (NDAs), or non-compete clauses you signed. These documents may include terms about the ownership of ideas or inventions conceived during your employment.\n\n2. **Intellectual Property**: In many jurisdictions, if an idea was developed as part of your job duties, or if company resources were used to develop it, the company may claim ownership of the idea, even if it was never productized.\n\n3. **Documentation**: If you can demonstrate that the idea was solely your own and was not developed using company resources, you may have a stronger case for pursuing it independently.\n\n4. **Nursery of Ideas**: If the idea was pitched publicly but not pursued, you may have more freedom to develop it. However, this can be complex if the company has any prior claims or internal policies regarding new ideas.\n\n5. **Legal Advice**: It\u2019s wise to consult with a legal expert specializing in intellectual property law. They can provide guidance tailored to your specific situation and jurisdiction.\n\n6. **Ethical Considerations**: Beyond legalities, consider the ethical implications of building on an idea you pitched. Maintaining positive relationships and professional integrity can be important in your career.\n\nIn summary, while it might be possible to build a product based on your idea, it's crucial to evaluate legal and ethical considerations first.",
